<div id="review_1218486026" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1218486026" />
    <a title="Erose" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25830701-erose"><img alt="Erose" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1426636020p2/25830701.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1218486026?book_show_action=true">May 11, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Erose" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Erose" href="/user/show/25830701-erose">Erose</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/25830701-erose?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1218486026" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer785905089872528304">The idea that a family built on facade would be forced to a reckoning by an event they can&apos;t ignore is one I found very believable. That reckoning, and the ways it looks different for the different characters, is emotionally resonant for me every time I read this book -- and by now it&apos;s been several times. <br/><br/>I enjoy that each character builds her particular facade on different underlying assumptions, meaning the cracks don&apos;t come from the same places and the characters interact with the early shoc</span>
  <span id="freeText785905089872528304" style="display:none">The idea that a family built on facade would be forced to a reckoning by an event they can't ignore is one I found very believable. That reckoning, and the ways it looks different for the different characters, is emotionally resonant for me every time I read this book -- and by now it's been several times. <br /><br />I enjoy that each character builds her particular facade on different underlying assumptions, meaning the cracks don't come from the same places and the characters interact with the early shock in ways that are true to their own fault lines. <br /><br />I enjoy the sheer number of thematic elements expressed through food, and the ways Malladi uses food to show so many things in such a short book. The different characters' relationship to food in general and main character Devi's cooking in particular symbolize many things about them, and I found that an effective way to do it. <br /><br />In general, Malladi is not always as subtle as she might be in this book and she her use of storytelling tools can be a little graceless in spots, but in my opinion it doesn't damage the overall impact of the book. There are still things to find in "Serving Crazy With Curry" multiple readings in. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="785905089872528304" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


