<span id="freeTextContainer15143936292245359870"><strong>Cooking suicide marriages that don&apos;t work</strong><br/><br/> The Veturis are shell shocked when their daughter Devi tries to kill herself. They cannot fathom why she would want to do that to herself. She comes back home and stops talking to people. Instead, she begins to cook up a storm. <br/> The whole family is forced to take a look at themselves and their relationships. Is it really what it seems like on the surface? Are Avi and Saroj really happy, with each other or their children? Is Shobha, Devi&apos;s sister, happy w</span>
  <span id="freeText15143936292245359870" style="display:none"><strong>Cooking suicide marriages that don't work</strong><br /><br /> The Veturis are shell shocked when their daughter Devi tries to kill herself. They cannot fathom why she would want to do that to herself. She comes back home and stops talking to people. Instead, she begins to cook up a storm. <br /> The whole family is forced to take a look at themselves and their relationships. Is it really what it seems like on the surface? Are Avi and Saroj really happy, with each other or their children? Is Shobha, Devi's sister, happy with her marriage to Girish?<br /> For some reason, I was perpetually confused between Shobha and Saroj. The writing will keep you on the edge of your seat. Kept me up reading all night for sure. Every chapter has a twist, something that you didn't see coming. The recipes interspersed between the chapters are the icing on the cake</span>
